\begin_layout Standard

\size large
This paper presents the implementation of a C++ converter for modelling a solar power plant with an inverter and integrating it into the dTwin environment.
 The model uses XML configuration files to define the parameters of the photovoltaic system,
 inverter and connection bus,
 while the GUI enables the selection of the test system,
 operating scenario and output dTwin model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The solar power plant is modelled through the available DC power,
 which depends on irradiance,
 cell temperature and the rated parameters of the PV field.
 The inverter limits the active AC power according to its rated power and determines the reactive power based on the selected power factor.
 After conversion,
 a dTwin DAE model with first-order dynamic equations is generated,
 describing the response of the active AC power,
 reactive power and available DC power.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size large
The implemented converter supports the test cases 
\shape italic
case9
\shape default
,
 
\shape italic
case30
\shape default
,
 
\shape italic
case118
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
case300
\shape default
,
 displays the main results in MW/MVAr and in the per-unit system,
 and uses natID dense and sparse matrix structures.
 The project demonstrates the workflow from XML configuration and GUI plugin interaction to dTwin model generation and graphical result visualization.
\end_layout

